	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Cereals sector policy in Benin and the impact of regional trade</h1>

			
			<h4>
												22 April 2013
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>USDA has published a review of the cereals sector in Benin. It highlights the government’s policy commitment to boosting local production, modernising agriculture and promoting agribusiness, with the long-term vision of becoming “a major exporter of agricultural products by 2025”. The renewed emphasis on expanding agricultural production is attributed to the experience of the 2008 food price crisis, despite the fact that, according to the USDA, “world market prices do not impact local prices for corn.”</p><p>There is seen as being considerable scope to improve yields (raising them from an average of 1 tonne/ha to 2 tonnes/ha). However, this is currently “hindered by lack of infrastructure, lack of mechanization, lack of rural credit, inefficient and insufficient use of fertiliser, insecticides, and seeds (inputs), soil fertility, and low yields”, as well as the effects of climate change on rainfall patterns.</p><p>The USDA analysis reviews recent trends in production and outlines the policy measures and institutional arrangements in the cereals sectors, in a context where 11.8% of the government budget is allocated to the agricultural sector.</p><p>Maize is a central part of the diet of the majority of Beninese, and is an “important component of poultry feed”. In marketing year (MY) 2012/13, maize production is expected to be 75% of total grain output (1.15 million tonnes out of a total coarse grain production of 1.541 million tonnes), slightly down on the 1.25 million tonnes produced in 2011/12. USDA states that ‘the combination of systematic intervention by the government and support by international donors has resulted in increased cereals production.’</p><p><b>Benin: Production of maize, sorghum and millet production 2010/11–2012/13 (tonnes)</b></p><table class="renderedtable" border="1" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0">
<tr>
<td width="73" valign="top">  &nbsp;
  </td><td width="151" valign="top">  <p class=" text-center">MY 2010/11</p><p class=" text-center">(Oct –Sep)</p>
  </td><td width="142" valign="top">  <p class=" text-center">MY 2011/12</p><p class=" text-center">(Oct –Sep)</p>
  </td><td width="151" valign="top">  <p class=" text-center">MY 2012/13</p><p class=" text-center">(Oct –Sep)</p>
  </td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td width="73" valign="top">  Maize
  </td><td width="151" valign="top">  1,150,000
  </td><td width="142" valign="top">  1,250,000
  </td><td width="151" valign="top">  1,150,000
  </td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td width="73" valign="top">  Sorghum
