  </td><td width="142" valign="top">  60,000
  </td><td width="151" valign="top">  27,000
  </td>
</tr>

</table>
<p>Source: USDA (see below), extracted from tables, pp. 5–6.</p><p>While world market prices are held to have little effect on local prices, the activities of regional traders strongly influence prices in some markets. USDA estimates that in the north, about half of domestic maize production is exported to Niger and Mali (according to USDA spot checks, traders from Niger offer prices on average 37% higher than local prices), while in the south, Nigerian traders push up local prices.</p><p>In terms of policy measures the Benin government is committed to free seed distribution and the provision of subsidised fertilisers (a 50% subsidy) through SONAPRA, the <i>Société Nationale pour la promotion agricole</i>. Farmers increasingly see this as an entitlement, since they have “little or no financial means to buy either seeds or fertiliser at market prices.” The government agency ONASA, the <i>Office National d’Appui à la Sécurité Alimentaire</i>, “buys and stores corn and rice to resell between harvests to smooth out market supplies and limit price surges”. The cereals sector is highly regulated, with private sector operators effectively acting as agents between producers and government agencies on the input side (ONASA) and marketing side (SONAPRA), and international agencies providing financing.</p><p>The government has made policy commitments to both diversification and the promotion of value-added processing, through the construction of “agricultural processing plants to process perishable products for export and local consumption”. Currently 30% of coarse grain production and 60% of vegetable production is lost due to poor post-harvest storage and processing practices. However USDA questions the government’s commitment to diversification, maintaining that it “continues to support cotton production the most heavily”.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>USDA, ‘Benin coarse grains and rice report’, <i>GAIN Report</i>, 29 January 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://gain.fas.usda.gov/Recent%20GAIN%20Publications/Benin%20Coarse%20Grains%20and%20Rice%20Report%20_Lagos_Benin_1-29-2013.pdf " target="_self">http://gain.fas.usda.gov/Recent%20GAIN%20Publications/Benin%20Coarse%20G...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>According to the African Development Bank, Benin, with vast land resources, has considerable scope for diversification and growth in the agricultural sector. Currently only 17% of its arable land is farmed. The availability of productive land provides considerable scope for the development of crops such as rice, maize, vegetables and pineapples for national, regional and overseas markets.</p><p>Despite the government’s commitment to diversification, cotton continues to attract most government investment and dominates the country’s agricultural sector, accounting for about 50–80% of merchandise exports and 10–15% of GDP. Although, potentially, cotton industry development and expanded cereals production are not mutually exclusive, there would appear to be a need to attract more private sector investment in both the provision of inputs and marketing of products, if current government services are not to be overwhelmed.</p><p>Benin is well placed to serve the huge Nigerian market and sits astride the transit routes for land-locked countries. At the level of informal trade these opportunities are being extensively exploited, with informal trade far exceeding official trade.</p><p>Against this background, the Regional Economic Communities (RECs) have been trying to improve market structures and design and implement measures to ease trade flows at the domestic and regional levels, with the aim of bringing this informal trade into the formal economy. This can be seen as essential, since the current situation is leading to the use of restrictive intra-regional trade measures, such as import bans and on a daily basis serves to undermine the effectiveness of national agricultural development strategies.</p><p>However, substantive progress on a coordinated basis at the regional level continues to prove elusive.</p>
		</div>
		
